User Permissions:
=================
          Type    users/owners     group    others
                      u             g        o
          -        rwx              r--     r--
R => 4
W => 2
X => 1

chmod 700 file Name/folder Name  ==> either owner or root user can only change the access levels

OWENERSHIP:
===========
Only root user can change the ownership of file/folders

chown -R <user>:<group>  <file/folder Name>  ===> -R recursively applies ownership inside folder files also.

EMPLOYEE JOIN ORG:
==================
1. He Generates keys locally
2. Sends public key to admin
3. Admin first creates user in server and automatically /home/user directory gets creates for that user. Admin now creates .ssh folder inside this.
4. Inside .ssh folder he will create a file name with authorized_keys and paste public keys shared by user.
5. Permissions for .ssh folder is 700
6. Permissions for authorized_keys max 600
7. Change Ownership to user itself chown user:user -R .ssh/
9. Add user to devsecops group  by ==> usermod -aG devsecops user
10. Also Create a file name with devsecops inside /etc/sudoers.d/ and add content %devsecops ALL(ALL:ALL) NOPASSWD:ALL it will enable sudo access to user
11. User can now login 
      ssh -i <his pvt key> <his username>@IP


PACKAGE MANAGEMENT:
===================
yum - old redhat pkg manager
dnf - latest redhat pkg manager
apt-get or apt - Ubuntu pkg manager

with sudo 
dnf install pkg-name
dnf remove pkg-name
dnf list installed           ==> /etc/yum.repos.d    here all URL's configured
dnf list avaialble
dnf search pkg-name


SERVICE MANAGEMENT:
===================
      0 - 65535  ports
https = 443 port
ssh   = 22 port

with sudo
systemctl start service-name
systemctl stop service-name
systemctl status service-name
systemctl enable service-name
systemctl disable service-name
systemctl restart service-name



NETWORK MANAGEMENT:
==================
netstat -lntp  ==> to see what services and ports are running and opened













